</blockquote>

<p>is so well known, has given us one of the best modern versions of this Christmas hymn of Gerhardtâ€™s. Her stanzas correspond as follows:</p>

<p>Gerhardt (Cox): 1 (1), 2 (2), 3 (3), 5 (4), 6 (5), 7 (6), 18 (7), 19 (8), 20 (9)</p>

<p>Miss Cox makes a less personal appeal to the worshipper and thereby loses much that is so excellent and characteristic of Gerhardt; instead of keeping the pronoun in the singular, â€œSo fasz <em>ich</em>â€ (stanza 18) â€œDu bist <em>mein</em> Hauptâ€ (stanza 19) and â€œ<em>Ich</em> will dein Allelujaâ€ (stanza 20), she has respectively â€œ<em>Our</em> love grows bold,â€ â€œThou art <em>our</em> Head,â€ and â€œ<em>Our</em> hallelujahs.â€ If her poem is rather more polished, Gerhardtâ€™s is certainly the more direct, as witness these stanzas:</p>

<p>Gerhardt (stanza 7)</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>Du kehrst in fremder Hausung ein,<br />
Und sind doch alle Himmel dein;<br />
Trinkst Milch aus deiner Mutter Brust<br />
Und bist doch selbst der Engel Lust. Â Â Â </p>
</blockquote>

<p>Cox (stanza 6)</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>Thou who both heaven and earth dost sway,<br />
In strangersâ€™ inn are fain to stay;<br />
And though thy power makes angels blest,<br />
